'''Iliman Cheikh Baroy Ndiaye''' (born 6 March 2000) is a professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[wide midfielder]] for [[Premier League]] club [[Everton F.C.|Everton]]. Born in France, he plays for the [[Senegal national football team|Senegal national team]].

==Club career==
===Early career===
Ndiaye began playing football with the French clubs Rouen Sapins, [[FC Rouen|Rouen]], and [[Olympique de Marseille|Marseille]] before moving to Senegal with [[AS Dakar Sacré-Cœur|Dakar Sacré-Cœur]]. His father moved to England and Ndiaye joined him where he joined the youth side of [[Boreham Wood F.C.|Boreham Wood]], also playing Sunday League matches with [[Rising Ballers Kensington F.C.|Rising Ballers]] to keep fit, in addition to representing his school [[Westminster Academy, London|Westminster Academy]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2022/dec/03/iliman-ndiayes-rise-from-sunday-league-to-senegal-world-cup-ace|title=Iliman Ndiaye's rise from Sunday league to Senegal World Cup ace|first=Will|last=Unwin|date=3 December 2022|newspaper=The Guardian}}</ref><ref name=":0" /> In November 2017, Ndiaye signed his first contract with [[Boreham Wood F.C.|Boreham Wood]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=21 November 2017 |title=Iliman Ndiaye signs pro deal |url=https://www.borehamwoodfootballclub.co.uk/uncategorized/iliman-ndiaye-signs-pro-deal/ |access-date=3 February 2024 |website=Boreham Wood FC}}</ref>

===Sheffield United===
On 31 August 2019, Ndiaye signed with [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wiwsport.com/2019/08/31/mercato-iliman-ndiaye-signe-a-sheffield-united-pour-trois-ans/|title=Mercato: Iliman Ndiaye signe à Sheffield United pour trois ans – Mercato|date=31 August 2019}}</ref> He joined [[Hyde United F.C.|Hyde United]] on loan for the latter half of the 2019–20 season.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestar.co.uk/sport/football/sheffield-united/free-scoring-midfielder-sheffield-united-squad-first-time-who-iliman-ndiaye-3110603|title=A free-scoring midfielder in the Sheffield United squad for the first time – who is Iliman Ndiaye?|website=thestar.co.uk|date=23 January 2021 }}</ref> He made his professional debut with Sheffield United as a late substitute in a 5–0 [[Premier League]] loss to [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]] on 14 March 2021.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://uk.soccerway.com/matches/2021/03/14/england/premier-league/leicester-city-fc/sheffield-united-fc/3344407/|title=Leicester City vs. Sheffield United – 14 March 2021 – Soccerway|publisher=Soccerway}}</ref><ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/2506102/2021/04/28/iliman-ndiaye-northern-premier-league-to-top-flight/|title='He was like a FIFA cheat code in their team': Iliman Ndiaye, the young star who swapped the Northern Premier League for the top flight in a year|publisher=theathletic.com (Archived)|date=28 April 2021|access-date=8 September 2023|archive-date=23 April 2023|archive-url=https://archive.today/20230423203803/https://theathletic.com/2506102/2021/04/28/iliman-ndiaye-northern-premier-league-to-top-flight/|url-status=bot: unknown}}</ref> On his full Sheffield United debut, he scored twice against [[Peterborough United F.C.|Peterborough United]] on 11 September in a 6–2 win.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/58444600 |title=Sheff Utd 6–2 Peterborough |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=11 September 2021 |access-date=13 September 2021}}</ref> On 3 March 2023 in the [[2022–23 FA Cup|FA Cup]], he scored in the 79th minute against [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] to secure a 1–0 victory and ensure Sheffield United's place in the quarter-finals.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/mar/01/sheffield-united-tottenham-fa-cup-fifth-round-match-report |title= Sheffield United stun Tottenham in FA Cup thanks to Iliman Ndiaye's solo goal |work=[[The Guardian]] | date= 1 March 2023 |access-date=2 March 2023}}</ref>

===Marseille===
On 1 August 2023, Ndiaye signed for [[Ligue 1]] club [[Olympique de Marseille|Marseille]], one of his former youth clubs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.om.fr/fr/actualites/4803/equipe-1ere/78042-iliman-ndiaye-est-olympien|title=Iliman Ndiaye est olympien !|publisher=OM.fr|date=1 August 2023|language=fr}}</ref> The transfer fee was a reported £20&nbsp;million.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/66377243|title=Iliman Ndiaye: Sheffield United 'reluctantly accept' Marseille's offer for Senegal striker|work=BBC Sport|date=1 August 2023}}</ref> He made his debut on 12 August in a 2–1 win against [[Stade de Reims|Reims]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eurosport.com/football/ligue-1/2023-2024/live-olympique-de-marseille-stade-de-reims_mtc1447591/live.shtml |title=Olympique de Marseille 2–1 Stade de Reims |publisher=Eurosport |date=12 August 2023}}</ref>

===Everton===
On 3 July 2024, [[Premier League]] club [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] announced the signing of Ndiaye on a five-year deal for an undisclosed fee. His debut goal for the club was against [[Doncaster Rovers F.C.|Doncaster Rovers]] in the second round of the [[2024–25 EFL Cup|EFL Cup]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.evertonfc.com/news/2024/july/03/everton-/|title=Everton Sign Ndiaye|publisher=Everton|date=3 July 2024|language=en}}</ref>

On 18 May 2025, Ndiaye scored the last goals for Everton at [[Goodison Park]], scoring both goals against [[Southampton FC|Southampton]] in a 2–0 win for the Toffees.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/articles/cly31g20ygvo|title='The old place will live on – but this was end of an era for Goodison Park'|publisher=BBC|date=18 May 2025|accessdate=18 May 2025}}</ref> He was also subsequently named Man of the Match.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2025/05/18/everton-vs-southampton-latest-updates-goodison-park-finale/|date=18 May 2025|accessdate=18 May 2025|website=The Daily Telegraph|title='Operation Farewell Goodison' could not have been scripted any better}}</ref> Later that year, on 24 August, he scored the first goal for Everton at [[Everton Stadium|Hill Dickinson Stadium]] in the Premier League, in a 2–0 victory against [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.premierleague.com/en/news/4387389/everton-v-brighton-match-report-premier-league-22-august-2025 |title=Everton beat Brighton in first match at Hill Dickinson Stadium |publisher=Premier League |date=24 August 2025 }}</ref>

==International career==
Ndiaye was born in France to a Senegalese father and French mother.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.seneweb.com/blogs/dakartimes/le-futur-lionel-messi-est-t-il-senegalais_b_4.html|title=Le futur Lionel Messi est-t-il Sénégalais ? &#124; Seneweb Blogs|date=14 March 2021|website=dakartimes}}</ref> He debuted with the [[Senegal national football team|Senegal national team]] in a 3–1 [[2023 Africa Cup of Nations qualification]] win over [[Benin national football team|Benin]] in the 67th minute when he was substituted on for [[Boulaye Dia]] on 4 June 2022.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dakaractu.com/Iliman-Ndiaye-apres-Senegal-Benin-3-1-J-ai-eu-des-frissons-quand-les-supporters-ont-crie-mon-nom_a219800.html|title=Iliman Ndiaye après Sénégal-Bénin (3–1) : " J'ai eu des frissons quand les supporters ont crié mon nom! "|website=DAKARACTU.COM}}</ref>

In November 2022, Ndiaye was named in the final squad for the [[2022 FIFA World Cup]] in Qatar.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/news/iliman-ndiayes-extraordinary-rise-sunday-28505510|title=Iliman Ndiaye's extraordinary rise from Sunday League football to Qatar World Cup|website=[[Daily Mirror]] |date=18 November 2022 |access-date=8 September 2023|archive-date=23 April 2023|archive-url=https://archive.today/20230423203447/https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/news/iliman-ndiayes-extraordinary-rise-sunday-28505510|url-status=bot: unknown}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2022/dec/03/iliman-ndiayes-rise-from-sunday-league-to-senegal-world-cup-ace|title=Iliman Ndiaye's rise from Sunday league to Senegal World Cup ace|newspaper=The Guardian |date=3 December 2022 |last1=Unwin |first1=Will }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/senegal/story/4826215/senegals-iliman-ndiaye-is-a-great-world-cup-story|title=Iliman Ndiaye's remarkable World Cup journey with Senegal is just the beginning|publisher=ESPN|date=7 December 2022 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/3758702/2022/11/21/iliman-ndiaye-world-cup-senegal/|title=How Senegal's Iliman Ndiaye went from unused Sheffield United substitute to the World Cup in 14 months|publisher=theathletic.com (Archived)|access-date=8 September 2023|archive-date=29 November 2022|archive-url=https://archive.today/20221129175241/https://theathletic.com/3758702/2022/11/21/iliman-ndiaye-world-cup-senegal/|url-status=bot: unknown |last1=Sutcliffe |first1=Richard }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11096/12760028/iliman-ndiaye-sheffield-united-and-senegal-forward-is-a-special-talent-who-went-from-non-league-to-world-cup|title=Iliman Ndiaye: Sheffield United and Senegal forward is a special talent who went from non-League to World Cup|publisher=skysports.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestar.co.uk/sport/football/sheffield-united/sheffield-united-he-had-three-bloody-lungs-how-senegals-iliman-ndiaye-reached-the-world-cup-3925034|title='He had three bloody lungs' – How Senegal's Iliman Ndiaye reached the World Cup|date=21 November 2022 |publisher=thestar.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestar.co.uk/sport/football/sheffield-united/iliman-ndiaye-the-inside-story-of-sheffield-united-stars-journey-from-non-league-to-world-cup-3927375|title=Iliman Ndiaye: The inside story of Sheffield United star's journey from non-league to World Cup|date=22 November 2022 |publisher=thestar.co.uk}}</ref> He appeared as a substitute in Senegal's second group match, assisting [[Bamba Dieng]]'s goal as the team beat hosts [[Qatar national football team|Qatar]] 3–1. He went on to start the team's third group match against [[Ecuador national football team|Ecuador]] and round of 16 loss to [[England national football team|England]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espn.com.au/football/story/_/id/37634596/senegal-iliman-ndiaye-great-world-cup-story|title=Iliman Ndiaye's remarkable World Cup journey with Senegal is just the beginning|date=7 December 2022|access-date=1 January 2024|publisher=ESPN}}</ref>

On 24 March 2023, Ndiaye scored his first international goal in a 5–1 victory against [[Mozambique national football team|Mozambique]] during an Africa Cup of Nations qualifier.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/match/_/gameId/634731 |title=Senegal 5–1 Mozambique |publisher=ESPN |date=24 March 2023 }}</ref>

In December 2023, he was named in Senegal's squad for the postponed [[2023 Africa Cup of Nations]] held in the [[Ivory Coast]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/africa/67840713|title=Afcon 2023: Senegal and Sadio Mane set for defence of title|date=29 December 2023|access-date=1 January 2024|work=BBC Sport Africa}}</ref> He appeared as a substitute in all four of the team's matches, assisting [[Lamine Camara]]'s second goal in the opening 3–0 win over [[Gambia national football team|The Gambia]] and scoring the second goal of a 2–0 win against [[Guinea national football team|Guinea]] in the final group match.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/67989631|title=Afcon 2023: Guinea 0–2 Senegal – Holders top group with perfect record|date=23 January 2024|access-date=28 April 2025|website=BBC Sport}}</ref>

In 2025, Ndiaye was named to the Senegal squad for the [[2025 Africa Cup of Nations]] held in [[Morocco]]. Ndiaye appeared in all seven games in Senegal's campaign, and scored the only goal in the quarterfinal match against [[Mali national football team|Mali]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Superior Senegal beat Mali to advance to Cup of Nations semi-finals |url=https://www.reuters.com/sports/soccer/superior-senegal-advance-cup-nations-semi-finals-2026-01-09/ |newspaper=Reuters |date=9 January 2026 |access-date=18 January 2026}}</ref>

